article.headline: Vanderbilt bursts Arkansas' bubble after big win
article.linkText: Vanderbilt bursts Arkansas' bubble after big win
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Look no further than Arkansas to understand the rigors of the Southeastern Conference.

One game after knocking off then-No. 2 Louisiana State, the Lady Razorbacks (No. 7 ESPN/USA Today, No. 8 AP) saw Jenni Benningfield score a career-high 28 points and grab 10 rebounds for her seventh double-double of the season in a 76-59 loss Thursday night to Vanderbilt (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP).

"There are a lot of good teams in this league,'' Arkansas coach Gary Blair said. "If you shoot 72 percent, you're going to win.''

Vanderbilt (12-5, 2-2 Southeastern Conference) set a school record for field goal percentage, converting 29 of 40 shots despite playing without senior point guard Ashley McElhiney, who sprained her left ankle against Kentucky on Sunday.

The Commodores broke a 12-12 tie seven minutes into the game
with a 10-0 run and never trailed the rest of the way.

"I thought we were ready to play,'' Vanderbilt coach Melanie
Balcomb said. "Playing against Arkansas is so difficult, because
they're going to come at you and press and trap. It's difficult to
hold onto the ball. But if you can pass out of the trap, you're
going to have shots. We just wanted to attack, keep attacking and
keep scoring. You can't be too timid.''

Shameka Christon finished with 22 for Arkansas (16-3, 3-1).

"Benningfield and Anderson played like all-SEC performers,
which they are,'' Blair said.

Chantelle Anderson added 25 points and seven rebounds for
Vanderbilt.

Arkansas trailed 33-23 at halftime, then fell behind 48-33 with
13:36 left when Benningfield converted a three-point play.

The Lady Razorbacks scored 10 straight points to pull within
five.

Benningfield then scored a pair of baskets and had two of her
game-high six assists in a 9-2 Vanderbilt spurt. The Commodores
eventually led 72-49 with 2:40 remaining before Christon scored the
last 10 points for Arkansas.

"We all knew what we had to come out and do,'' said Benningfield, who had set a previous career high of 24 points in Sunday's win over Kentucky. "Everybody gave everything they could.''

Tia Battle scored also scored a career-high 15 points for Vanderbilt.
